o Edit] / \"The Perception Of Johnny Punter\" [US Radio Edit]\n* 1999: \"Incomplete\" (feat. [[Elisabeth Troy|Elisabeth Antwi]]) / \"Wake Up Call\" [Acoustic Version] / \"Incomplete\" [Demo Version Recorded At The Castle Marouatte France]\n* 2008: \"Arc Of The Curve\" [Single Edit] / \"Arc of the Curve\"\n* 2008: \"Zoe 25\" [Radio Edit] / \"Dark Star\" [Live In Amsterdam 2008] / \"13th Star\" [Live In Amsterdam 2008]\n* 2014: \"[[Blind to the Beautiful]]\"\n\n===EPs===\n* 2018: \"A Parley with Angels\"\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Fish (singer)}}\n*Official website (as of 2017) \u2013 {{Site|http://fishmusic.scot}}\n*Official website (old) \u2013 {{Site|http://www.fish-thecompany.com/}}\n*Official website (old) \u2013 {{Site|http://www.fishheads.club/}}\n*{{IMDb name|name=Fish|id=0279258}} provides information on Fish and his acting career.\n\n{{Fish (singer)}}\n{{Marillion}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fish}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Scottish male actors]]\n[[Category:Art rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Marillion members]]\n[[Category:People associated with Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:People educated at Dalkeith High School]]\n[[Category:People from Dalkeith]]\n[[Category:People from Midlothian]]\n[[Category:Scottish expatriates in Germany]]\n[[Category:Scottish male film actors]]\n[[Category:Scottish male singers]]\n[[Category:Scottish male television actors]]\n[[Category:Scottish rock singers]]\n[[Category:Scottish socialists]]\n[[Category:Scottish songwriters]]\n", "name_user": "1980fast", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCurrent live band:Capitalisation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fish_(singer)"}
{"title_page": "James Miller (parachutist)", "text_new": "{{short description|American parachutist and paraglider pilot}}\n{{Redirect|Fan Man|William Kotzwinkle's 1974 novel|The Fan Man}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                      = James Miller\n| image                     = \n| image_size                = \n| alt                       = \n| caption                   = \n| birth_name                = James Jarret Miller\n| birth_date                = {{birth date|1963|10|28|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place               = [[Havre de Grace, Maryland]], U.S.\n| death_cause               = Suicide by hanging\n| disappeared_date          = {{disappeared date and age|2002|9|22|1963|10|28}} \n| disappeared_place         = [[Kenai Peninsula]], [[Alaska]]     \n| body_discovered           = March 9, 2003, Kenai Peninsula, Alaska\n| nationality               = [[Americans|American]]\n| alma_mater                = [[University of Alaska Southeast|University of Alaska at Juneau]]\n| children                  = 1\n}}\n<!-- Spelling: US -->\n\n'''James Jarrett Miller''' (October 28, 1963 &ndash; c. September 22, 2002), also known as '''the Fan Man''', was an American [[parachute|parachutist]] and [[paragliding|paraglider]] pilot  known for his appearances at various sporting events. His most infamous appearance was the November 6, 1993 [[boxing]] [[Riddick Bowe vs. Evander Holyfield II|match]] between [[Evander Holyfield]] and [[Riddick Bowe]] at [[Caesars Palace]] on the [[Las Vegas Strip]] in [[Las Vegas, Nevada|Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]]. Fan Man made headlines in the [[United States]] when he used his [[Powered paragliding|powered paraglider]] to fly into the arena, eventually crashing into the side of the ring.\n\n==Background==\nMiller was born in [[Havre de Grace, Maryland|Havre de Grace]], [[Maryland]]. He had three younger brothers and two younger sisters. In 1975, the Miller family moved to a country home near the [[Canada\u2013United States border]]. The following year, the family relocated to [[Tok, Alaska]]. Miller later earned an associate degree in computer programming from the [[University of Alaska Southeast|University of Alaska at Juneau]]. In the late 1980s, he moved to [[Las Vegas]] where he was introduced to [[Paragliding|paragliders]].<ref name=\"joling\">{{cite web|url=http://peninsulaclarion.com/stories/032303/ala_032303ala0020001.shtml|title=Death claims flamboyant Fan Man|last=Joling|first=Dan|date=March 23, 2003|publisher=peninsulaclarion.com|accessdate=January 15, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050215095035/http://peninsulaclarion.com/stories/032303/ala_032303ala0020001.shtml|archivedate=February 15, 2005}}</ref>\n\nMiller had been interested in flying since childhood and quickly became a paragliding enthusiast. \nHe started with a jetpack tied to his back, and moved up to two-cycle aircraft engines which powered him through the skies above the desert. He began setting power-gliding records for altitude and distance, with a reputation for reckless daring.<ref>{{cite news| title=Obituary | newspaper=Anchorage Daily News| date=March 21, 2003}}</ref>\n\n==The Fan Man fight==\n{{Main article|Riddick Bowe vs. Evander Holyfield II}}\nMiller's first and most famous stunt happened on November 6, 1993 during the [[heavyweight]] title fight between Riddick Bowe and Evander Holyfield. Miller descended into the side of the ring area during the second minute of the seventh round of the fight, after circling [[Caesars Palace]] for ten minutes. The lines of his [[paraglider]] became tangled in the overhead lights, after which he landed on the top rope of the ring with his parachute still tangled in the lights. He tried to hang on with one foot and one hand on that top rope for a few seconds until he either fell or was dragged down into the crowd by spectators, his parachute ripping away from the lights above.\n\nFans and the fighters' security detail swarmed around him immediately and began attacking him. He was knocked unconscious during the attack.  One security officer reportedly struck Miller twenty times. He was rushed to a nearby hospital as spectators cut his paraglider into pieces for souvenirs. After his release from the hospital, Miller was taken to the [[Clark County, Nevada|Clark County]] Detention Center, where he was charged with dangerous flying and released on $200 bail. In an exclusive interview with British journalists after the bout, Miller categorized his ring crash as accidental and not intentional, claiming it was caused by mechanical problems.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1876&dat=19931111&id=-zcfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=G88EAAAAIBAJ&pg=6713,3676022|title=Fan Man says landing was accidental|date=November 11, 1993|work=Herald-Journal|page=D2}}</ref> Miller later joked, \"It was a heavyweight fight and I was the only guy who got knocked out.\"<ref name=\"davies\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/northamerica/usa/1426499/Deported-Palace-paraglider-kills-himself-in-Alaska.html|title=Deported Palace paraglider kills himself in Alaska|last=Davies|first=Caroline|date=April 3, 2003|publisher=telegraph.co.uk|accessdate=January 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe media immediately dubbed Miller \"Fan Man,\" for the [[paramotor]] (lightweight engine and propeller) attached to his harness.\n\n==Other stunts==\nOn January 9, 1994, Miller circled approximately 1,000 feet over the rim of the [[Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum]] on his paraglider during the [[Denver Broncos]]-[[Oakland Raiders|Los Angeles Raiders]] [[NFL]] playoff game. He landed in a park north of the Coliseum where he was arrested for interfering with a sporting event.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2245&dat=19940108&id=ODozAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ojIHAAAAIBAJ&pg=5330,897748|title=Glider buzzes Raiders game|date=January 10, 1994|work=Lodi News-Sentinel|page=15|accessdate=January 15, 2015}}</ref> Later that same month, he \"buzzed\", (flew low over), a [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]]-[[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] 4th round [[FA Cup]] [[association football|football]] match at [[Burnden Park]] in [[Bolton, England]]. After serving a seven-day prison sentence, Miller was [[deportation|deported]] by British authorities.<ref name=\"observer\"/>\n\nOn February 5 he was witnessed by British police paragliding along [[The Mall, London|The Mall]] before landing atop [[Buckingham Palace]]. He then removed his trousers revealing that he was painted green from the waist down.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1817&dat=19940206&id=fTkdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=2qUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5357,984357|title=Half-naked American lands on palace roof|date=February 6, 1994|work=The Tuscaloosa News|page=5A|accessdate=January 15, 2015}}</ref>  He was arrested without incident, fined \u00a3200 and was again deported.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/theroyalfamily/5377202/Buckingham-Palace-previous-security-breaches.html|title=Buckingham Palace: previous security breaches|date=May 24, 2009|publisher=telegraph.co.uk|accessdate=January 15, 2015}}</ref> He was banned from reentering the UK for life.<ref name=\"joling\"/>\n\nWhen asked by reporters what his motives were for staging these stunts, Miller never gave clear answers. He claimed that he intentionally landed in the ring to break up the Bowe vs. Holyfield match, claiming he was opposed to violence.<ref name=\"observer\">{{cite news| url=http://observer.guardian.co.uk/osm/story/0,,1337278,00.html | location=London | work=The Guardian | title=The 30 most outrageous sporting moments}}</ref> Miller's younger brother later said Miller staged the stunts because, \"He was basically bucking society. He was mocking our rules, making up his own as he went along, kind of just making a mockery of our society and the way it works and what our expectations are.\"<ref name=\"joling\"/>\n\n==Later years and death ==\nAfter returning to the United States, Miller received death threats for interrupting sporting events. In 1996, he relocated to [[Valdez, Alaska|Valdez]], [[Alaska]] where he lived in a hut with no indoor plumbing. He continued to fly [[ultralight aircraft]] and paragliders in the Alaskan [[wilderness]] and also gave lessons. Miller briefly worked for a computer company before opening his own computer business.<ref name=\"observer\"/> In 2001, he was diagnosed with [[coronary artery disease]] and underwent [[Coronary artery bypass surgery|double bypass surgery]]. There were complications and Miller developed health issues. He underwent two additional surgeries to correct issues caused by the first surgery, but continued to experience constant chest pains and ill health. Miller was unable to continue flying, paragliding and hiking because of his declining health. Due to mounting debts from medical bills, Miller was forced to close his computer business. He moved to [[Anchorage, Alaska|Anchorage]] in 2002, where he worked for a utility company.<ref name=\"joling\"/>\n\nOn September 22, 2002, Miller was reported missing after he disappeared earlier that morning while driving to the wilderness. His car was found near the Resurrection Pass Trail in [[Chugach National Forest]] on the [[Kenai Peninsula]]. A search was launched but was suspended on October 13.<ref name=\"joling\"/> On March 9, 2003, a group of hunters [[Trail blazing|bushwhacking]] through the woods on the peninsula found Miller's decomposing body. An autopsy revealed that Miller had hanged himself from a tree. Police said they believed Miller had chosen the remote Resurrection Pass Trail  and had veered deep off-trail in hopes that his body would not have been discovered for years, if ever.<ref>{{cite news|author=Tizon, Tomas Alex |date=March 6, 2005 |title=Alaska: the land of the lost |format=http |work=Los Angeles Times |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2002198453_alaska06.html |accessdate=November 28, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060427133403/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2002198453_alaska06.html |archivedate=April 27, 2006 }}</ref>  At the time of his death, Miller's girlfriend was pregnant with the couple's first child. She gave birth to their son shortly before Miller's body was discovered in March 2003.<ref name=\"observer\"/>\n\nAlthough Miller's disappearance and death were reported in the local press shortly after his body was found, his suicide did not become widely known outside Alaska until the latter part of 2003 when [[ESPN]] went searching for him to film a ''[[SportsCenter]]'' feature to be shown during the tenth anniversary of his stunt.\n\n==In popular culture==\n* [[Fox Sports Net]] ranked Miller crashing into the boxing ring during the Bowe vs. Holyfield match as its #1 \"Most Outrageous Sports Moment\".\n* An animated version of \"the Fan Man\" appears in ''[[The Simpsons]]'' episode \"[[The Homer They Fall]]\".<ref>{{cite video |people=Meyer, George |date=2006 |title=The Simpsons season 8 DVD commentary for the episode \"The Homer They Fall\" |medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of people who disappeared]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- This link doesn't exist any more\n * {{YouTube|eC1RmBHpsrA|Video highlight clip during Bowe-Holyfield 2, Round 7}} -->\n* {{YouTube|KgNarF2XmAY|''Sports Science'' recreates 'Fan Man' incident to evaluate Miller's flight trajectory}}\n* {{Find a Grave|95314080}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Miller, James}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:2002 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American people]]\n[[Category:American skydivers]]\n[[Category:Male suicides]]\n[[Category:Missing person cases in Alaska]]\n[[Category:People deported from the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People from Henderson, Nevada]]\n[[Category:People from Havre de Grace, Maryland]]\n[[Category:People from Valdez, Alaska]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople who committed suicide]]\n[[Category:Suicides by hanging in Alaska]]\n[[Category:University of Alaska Southeast alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American parachutist and paraglider pilot}}\n{{Redirect|Fan Man|William Kotzwinkle's 1974 novel|The Fan Man}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                      = James Miller\n| image                     = \n| image_size                = \n| alt                       = \n| caption                   = \n| birth_name                = James Jarret Miller\n| birth_date                = {{birth date|1963|10|28|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place               = [[Havre de Grace, Maryland]], U.S.\n| death_cause               = Suicide by hanging\n| disappeared_date          = {{disappeared date and age|2002|9|22|1963|10|28}} \n| disappeared_place         = [[Kenai Peninsula]], [[Alaska]]     \n| body_discovered           = March 9, 2003, Kenai Peninsula, Alaska\n| nationality               = [[Americans|American]]\n| alma_mater                = [[University of Alaska Southeast|University of Alaska at Juneau]]\n| children                  = 1\n}}\n<!-- Spelling: US -->\n\n'''James Jarrett Miller''' (October 28, 1963 &ndash; c. September 22, 2002), also known as '''the Fan Man''', was an American [[parachute|parachutist]] and [[paragliding|paraglider]] pilot  known for his appearances at various sporting events. His most infamous appearance was the November 6, 1993 [[boxing]] [[Riddick Bowe vs. Evander Holyfield II|match]] between [[Evander Holyfield]] and [[Riddick Bowe]] at [[Caesars Palace]] on the [[Las Vegas Strip]] in [[Las Vegas, Nevada|Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]]. Fan Man made headlines in the [[United States]] when he used his [[Powered paragliding|powered paraglider]] to fly into the arena, eventually crashing into the side of the ring.\n\n==Background==\nMiller was born in [[Havre de Grace, Maryland|Havre de Grace]], [[Maryland]]. He had three younger brothers and two younger sisters. In 1975, the Miller family moved to a country home near the [[Canada\u2013United States border]]. The following year, the family relocated to [[Tok, Alaska]]. Miller later earned an associate degree in computer programming from the [[University of Alaska Southeast|University of Alaska at Juneau]]. In the late 1980s, he moved to [[Las Vegas]] where he was introduced to [[Paragliding|paragliders]].<ref name=\"joling\">{{cite web|url=http://peninsulaclarion.com/stories/032303/ala_032303ala0020001.shtml|title=Death claims flamboyant Fan Man|last=Joling|first=Dan|date=March 23, 2003|publisher=peninsulaclarion.com|accessdate=January 15, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050215095035/http://peninsulaclarion.com/stories/032303/ala_032303ala0020001.shtml|archivedate=February 15, 2005}}</ref>\n\nMiller had been interested in flying since childhood and quickly became a paragliding enthusiast. \nHe started with a jetpack tied to his back, and moved up to two-cycle aircraft engines which powered him through the skies above the desert. He began setting power-gliding records for altitude and distance, with a reputation for reckless daring.<ref>{{cite news| title=Obituary | newspaper=Anchorage Daily News| date=March 21, 2003}}</ref>\n\n==The Fan Man fight==\n{{Main article|Riddick Bowe vs. Evander Holyfield II}}\nMiller's first and most famous stunt happened on November 6, 1993 during the [[heavyweight]] title fight between Riddick Bowe and Evander Holyfield. Miller descended into the side of the ring area during the second minute of the seventh round of the fight, after circling [[Caesars Palace]] for ten minutes. The lines of his [[paraglider]] became tangled in the overhead lights, after which he landed on the top rope of the ring with his parachute still tangled in the lights. He tried to hang on with one foot and one hand on that top rope for a few seconds until he either fell or was dragged down into the crowd by spectators, his parachute ripping away from the lights above.\n\nFans and the fighters' security detail swarmed around him immediately and began attacking him. He was knocked unconscious during the attack.  One security officer reportedly struck Miller twenty times. He was rushed to a nearby hospital as spectators cut his paraglider into pieces for souvenirs. After his release from the hospital, Miller was taken to the [[Clark County, Nevada|Clark County]] Detention Center, where he was charged with dangerous flying and released on $200 bail. In an exclusive interview with British journalists after the bout, Miller categorized his ring crash as accidental and not intentional, claiming it was caused by mechanical problems.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1876&dat=19931111&id=-zcfAAAAIBAJ&sjid=G88EAAAAIBAJ&pg=6713,3676022|title=Fan Man says landing was accidental|date=November 11, 1993|work=Herald-Journal|page=D2}}</ref> Miller later joked, \"It was a heavyweight fight and I was the only guy who got knocked out.\"<ref name=\"davies\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/northamerica/usa/1426499/Deported-Palace-paraglider-kills-himself-in-Alaska.html|title=Deported Palace paraglider kills himself in Alaska|last=Davies|first=Caroline|date=April 3, 2003|publisher=telegraph.co.uk|accessdate=January 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe media immediately dubbed Miller \"Fan Man,\" for the [[paramotor]] (lightweight engine and propeller) attached to his harness.\n\n==Other stunts==\nOn January 9, 1994, Miller circled approximately 1,000 feet over the rim of the [[Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum]] on his paraglider during the [[Denver Broncos]]-[[Oakland Raiders|Los Angeles Raiders]] [[NFL]] playoff game. He landed in a park north of the Coliseum where he was arrested for interfering with a sporting event.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2245&dat=19940108&id=ODozAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ojIHAAAAIBAJ&pg=5330,897748|title=Glider buzzes Raiders game|date=January 10, 1994|work=Lodi News-Sentinel|page=15|accessdate=January 15, 2015}}</ref> Later that same month, he \"buzzed\", (flew low over), a [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]]-[[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] 4th round [[FA Cup]] [[association football|football]] match at [[Burnden Park]] in [[Bolton, England]]. After serving a seven-day prison sentence, Miller was [[deportation|deported]] by British authorities.<ref name=\"observer\"/>\n\nOn February 5 he was witnessed by British police paragliding along [[The Mall, London|The Mall]] before landing atop [[Buckingham Palace]]. He then removed his trousers revealing that he was painted green from the waist down.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1817&dat=19940206&id=fTkdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=2qUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5357,984357|title=Half-naked American lands on palace roof|date=February 6, 1994|work=The Tuscaloosa News|page=5A|accessdate=January 15, 2015}}</ref>  He was arrested without incident, fined \u00a3200 and was again deported.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/theroyalfamily/5377202/Buckingham-Palace-previous-security-breaches.html|title=Buckingham Palace: previous security breaches|date=May 24, 2009|publisher=telegraph.co.uk|accessdate=January 15, 2015}}</ref> He was banned from reentering the UK for life.<ref name=\"joling\"/>\n\nWhen asked by reporters what his motives were for staging these stunts, Miller never gave clear answers. He claimed that he intentionally landed in the ring to break up the Bowe vs. Holyfield match, claiming he was opposed to violence.<ref name=\"observer\">{{cite news| url=http://observer.guardian.co.uk/osm/story/0,,1337278,00.html | location=London | work=The Guardian | title=The 30 most outrageous sporting moments}}</ref> Miller's younger brother later said Miller staged the stunts because, \"He was basically bucking society. He was mocking our rules, making up his own as he went along, kind of just making a mockery of our society and the way it works and what our expectations are.\"<ref name=\"joling\"/>\n\n==Later years and death ==\nAfter returning to the United States, Miller received death threats for interrupting sporting events. In 1996, he relocated to [[Valdez, Alaska|Valdez]], [[Alaska]] where he lived in a hut with no indoor plumbing. He continued to fly [[ultralight aircraft]] and paragliders in the Alaskan [[wilderness]] and also gave lessons. Miller briefly worked for a computer company before opening his own computer business.<ref name=\"observer\"/> In 2001, he was diagnosed with [[coronary artery disease]] and underwent [[Coronary artery bypass surgery|double bypass surgery]]. There were complications and Miller developed health issues. He underwent two additional surgeries to correct issues caused by the first surgery, but continued to experience constant chest pains and ill health. Miller was unable to continue flying, paragliding and hiking because of his declining health. Due to mounting debts from medical bills, Miller was forced to close his computer business. He moved to [[Anchorage, Alaska|Anchorage]] in 2002, where he worked for a utility company.<ref name=\"joling\"/>\n\nOn September 22, 2002, Miller was reported missing after he disappeared earlier that morning while driving to the wilderness. His car was found near the Resurrection Pass Trail in [[Chugach National Forest]] on the [[Kenai Peninsula]]. A search was launched but was suspended on October 13.<ref name=\"joling\"/> On March 9, 2003, a group of hunters [[Trail blazing|bushwhacking]] through the woods on the peninsula found Miller's decomposing body. An autopsy revealed that Miller had hanged himself from a tree. Police said they believed Miller had chosen the remote Resurrection Pass Trail  and had veered deep off-trail in hopes that his body would not have been discovered for years, if ever.<ref>{{cite news|author=Tizon, Tomas Alex |date=March 6, 2005 |title=Alaska: the land of the lost |format=http |work=Los Angeles Times |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2002198453_alaska06.html |accessdate=November 28, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060427133403/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2002198453_alaska06.html |archivedate=April 27, 2006 }}</ref>  At the time of his death, Miller's girlfriend was pregnant with the couple's first child. She gave birth to their son shortly before Miller's body was discovered in March 2003.<ref name=\"observer\"/>\n\nAlthough Miller's disappearance and death were reported in the local press shortly after his body was found, his suicide did not become widely known outside Alaska until the latter part of 2003 when [[ESPN]] went searching for him to film a ''[[SportsCenter]]'' feature to be shown during the tenth anniversary of his stunt.\n\n==In popular culture==\n* [[Fox Sports Net]] ranked Miller crashing into the boxing ring during the Bowe vs. Holyfield match as its #1 \"Most Outrageous Sports Moment\".\n* An animated version of \"the Fan Man\" appears in ''[[The Simpsons]]'' episode \"[[The Homer They Fall]]\".<ref>{{cite video |people=Meyer, George |date=2006 |title=The Simpsons season 8 DVD commentary for the episode \"The Homer They Fall\" |medium=DVD |publisher=20th Century Fox}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of people who disappeared]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{YouTube|eC1RmBHpsrA|Video highlight clip during Bowe-Holyfield 2, Round 7}}\n* {{YouTube|KgNarF2XmAY|''Sports Science'' recreates 'Fan Man' incident to evaluate Miller's flight trajectory}}\n* {{Find a Grave|95314080}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Miller, James}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:2002 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American people]]\n[[Category:American skydivers]]\n[[Category:Male suicides]]\n[[Category:Missing person cases in Alaska]]\n[[Category:People deported from the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People from Henderson, Nevada]]\n[[Category:People from Havre de Grace, Maryland]]\n[[Ca